{"id":"1910.07086","submitter":"Tobias Kramer","authors":"Eric J Heller and Ragnar Fleischmann and Tobias Kramer","title":"Branched Flow","comments":"7 pages, 6 figures","journal-ref":"Physics Today vol 74, 12, p. 44 (2021)","doi":"10.1063/PT.3.4902","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.class-ph physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In many physical situations involving diverse length scales, waves or rays\nrepresenting them travel through media characterized by spatially smooth,\nrandom, modest refactive index variations. \"Primary\" diffraction (by individual\nsub-wavelength features) is absent. Eventually the weak refraction leads to\nimperfect focal \"cusps\". Much later, a statistical regime characterized by\nmomentum diffusion is manifested. An important intermediate regime is often\noverlooked, one that is diffusive only in an ensemble sense. Each realization\nof the ensemble possesses dramatic ray limit structure that guides the waves\n(in the same sense that ray optics is used to design lens systems). This\nstructure is a universal phenomenon called branched flow. Many important\nphenomena develop in this intermediate regime. Here we give examples and some\nof the physics of this emerging field.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 16 Oct 2019 17:24:13 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-12-14"}
{"id":"1910.07439","submitter":"Phillip Cussen Burke","authors":"Phillip C. Burke, Jan Wiersig, Masudul Haque","title":"Non-Hermitian scattering on a tight-binding lattice","comments":"v2: Updated with changes made for publication in Phys. Rev. A. 14\n  pages, 14 figures. v1: 12 pages, 14 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 102, 012212 (2020)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.102.012212","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph cond-mat.other","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We analyze the scattering dynamics and spectrum of a quantum particle on a\ntight-binding lattice subject to a non-Hermitian (purely imaginary) local\npotential. The reflection, transmission and absorption coefficients are studied\nas a function of the strength of this absorbing potential. The system is found\nto have an exceptional point at a certain strength of the potential. Unusually,\nall (or nearly all) of the spectrum pairs up into mutually coalescing\neigenstate pairs at this exceptional point. At large potential strengths, the\nabsorption coefficient decreases and the effect of the imaginary potential is\nsimilar to that of a real potential. We quantify this similarity by utilizing\nproperties of a localized eigenstate.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 16 Oct 2019 16:02:05 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 17 Jul 2020 10:40:03 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-07-20"}
